Security Reflection

While completing this personal security audit, I realized that cybersecurity is not only about protecting systems but also about developing secure habits in daily life. I reviewed my device security settings, password management practices, and online accounts to identify potential weaknesses. I found that keeping my operating system updated, using antivirus software, and enabling the firewall are essential for protecting my computer against cyber threats.

I also understood the importance of creating strong and unique passwords for every online account. Password reuse can make multiple accounts vulnerable if one password is compromised. Enabling Multi-Factor Authentication provides an additional layer of security and significantly reduces the risk of unauthorized access.

During this assessment, I also learned about common cyber threats such as phishing, malware, ransomware, social engineering, and data breaches. These attacks can cause financial loss, identity theft, and data compromise if proper precautions are not taken. Awareness and careful online behavior are among the best defenses against such threats.

Based on this assessment, I plan to improve my cybersecurity practices by enabling MFA on all important accounts, regularly updating my passwords, avoiding suspicious emails and links, and keeping my operating system and applications updated. I will also continue learning about cybersecurity to stay informed about emerging threats.

Overall, this task helped me understand that cybersecurity is everyone's responsibility. Practicing good cyber hygiene and following security best practices can greatly reduce the chances of becoming a victim of cybercrime.